7 Sec. 2.6. Chapter 449A of NRS is hereby amended by adding
8 thereto a new section to read as follows:
9 The parent or legal guardian of a newborn child who is
10 receiving care in a neonatal intensive care unit of a hospital has
11 the right to:
12 1. Receive clear, honest and timely updates concerning the
13 condition, treatment plan and prognosis of the newborn child in a
14 language that the parent or legal guardian understands.
15 2. Be near the newborn child, except in emergency situations
16 or if other safety concerns exist, and participate in the daily
17 rounds and decision making relating to the child.
18 3. Be informed of and provide consent to all treatments for
19 and procedures performed on the newborn child, except in
20 emergency situations.
21 4. As medically appropriate, hold and touch the newborn
22 child.
23 5. Access lactation support, receive information on
24 breastfeeding and the expression of breast milk and access options
25 for the safe storage of breast milk that are within the existing
26 capabilities of the hospital, if the parent or legal guardian chooses
27 to breastfeed the newborn child.
28 6. Receive information concerning resources relating to the
29 mental health of the parent or legal guardian, including, without
30 limitation, support groups, counseling services or peer networks.
31 7. Ask questions and voice concerns to the medical staff of
32 the hospital.
33 8. Request and, when feasible, receive accommodations for
34 religious or cultural needs, including, without limitation, spiritual
35 support or dietary needs.
36 9. Be informed concerning the process for discharge from the
37 hospital and any potential long-term needs of the newborn child.
38 10. Receive guidance on applying for and receiving benefits
39 under private insurance, the Supplemental Security Income
40 Program, as defined in NRS 422A.075, and Medicaid, where
41 applicable.
42 11. An environment in the hospital that acknowledges the
43 role of the parent or legal guardian as a caregiver, including,
44 without limitation, reasonable accommodations for the comfort
45 and privacy of the parent or legal guardian and the ability of the
